04409nam a22006255i 9780292794665DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212008txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927946657 a10.7560/7145022doi  a(DE-B1597)587235  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 7aPER0000002bisacsh04a791.45/61 aBenavides, O. Hugo, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDrugs, Thugs, and Divas :bTelenovelas and Narco-Dramas in Latin America /cO. Hugo Benavides. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2008  a1 online resource (245 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tAcknowledgments -- tOne. Melodrama as Ambiguous Signifier: Latin American Telenovelas and Narco-Dramas -- tPart One -- tTwo. Seeing Xica and the Melodramatic Unveiling of Colonial Desire -- tThree. Producing the Global West through Latin Tales of Seduction and Envy -- tFour. Karen’s Seduction: The Racial Politics of Appropriate Dinner Guests -- tFive. A Mother’s Wrath and the Complex Disjuncturing of Class -- tPart Two -- tSix. Being Narco: The Evolution of a Continental Sensibility -- tSeven. Saintly Figures and Icons: The Migration of a Continental Dream -- tEight. La Reina del Sur: Gender, Racial, and National Contestations of Regional Identity -- tNine. Sex, Drugs, and Cumbia: The Hybrid Nature of Culture -- tTen. Conclusion: The Postcolonial Politics of Melodrama -- tPostscript. Ugly Betty -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSoap opera speaks a universal language, presenting characters and plots that resonate far beyond the culture that creates them. Latin American soap operas—telenovelas—have found enthusiastic audiences throughout the Americas and Europe, as well as in Egypt, Russia, and China, while Mexican narco-dramas have become highly popular among Latinos in the United States. In this first comprehensive analysis of telenovelas and narco-dramas, Hugo Benavides assesses the dynamic role of melodrama in creating meaningful cultural images to explain why these genres have become so successful while more elite cultural productions are declining in popularity. Benavides offers close readings of the Colombian telenovelas Betty la fea (along with its Mexican and U.S. reincarnations La fea más bella and Ugly Betty), Adrián está de visita, and Pasión de gavilanes; the Brazilian historical telenovela Xica; and a variety of Mexican narco-drama films. Situating these melodramas within concrete historical developments in Latin America, he shows how telenovelas and narco-dramas serve to unite peoples of various countries and provide a voice of rebellion against often-oppressive governmental systems. Indeed, Benavides concludes that as one of the most effective and lucrative industries in Latin America, telenovelas and narco-dramas play a key role in the ongoing reconfiguration of social identities and popular culture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aDrugs in motion pictures. 0aMotion pictureszLatin America. 0aTelevision soap operaszLatin America. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/71450240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292794665423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292794665/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK